WHEREAS the Convention on Biological Diversity was opened 
for signature at Rio De Janeiro, Brazil on 5 June 1992 and entered 
into  force  on  29  December  1993;

“advisory  body”  means  a  body  comprising  representatives  of 
indigenous  community  and  local  community  established  by  the 
Competent  Authority  under  subsection  9(2);

(a)  the  genetic  resources,  organisms,  microorganisms, 
derivatives and parts of the genetic resources, organisms, 
microorganisms  or  derivatives;

“clearing  house  mechanism”  means  a  web-based  information 
portal  established  by  the  National  Competent  Authority  under 
section  32;

“genetic  resource”  means  any  material  of  plant,  animal, 
microorganism, fungi or other origin that contains functional units 
of  heredity  and  that  has  actual  or  potential  value  for  humanity;

and who speak an aboriginal or a native language and habitually 
follow  and  embody  an  aboriginal’s  or  a  native’s  traditional  way 
of  life,  customs  and  beliefs;

“microorganism” means any organism of microscopic size and 
parts of organism of microscopic size, including sterile organisms, 
viruses  and  viroids;

“premises”  includes  any  hut,  shed,  structure,  platform,  house, 
building,  conveyance  and  land  whether  or  not  enclosed  or  built 
upon;

“propagating material” means any biological resource material 
including  material  of  plant  or  animal  origin  or  any  part  of  the 
biological resource material, used for multiplication or reproduction;

(e)  the  indigenous  community  and  local  community,  where 
the  resource  is  on  land  to  which  they  have  a  right  as 
established  by  law;

(c)  taking  biological  resource  that  has  been  cultivated  or 
tended for any purpose other than the purpose of research 
and  development;

(d)  taking  natural  produce  including  oils  and  honey  for 
any  purpose  other  than  the  purpose  of  research  and 
development;

(e)  to  create  awareness  and  to  provide  training,  education 
and  information  relating  to  access  and  benefit  sharing 
in  relation  to  a  biological  resource;

(f)  to keep and maintain a register of permits issued by the 
Competent  Authorities  and  information  relating  to  the 
permit;

(b)  to  maintain  a  record  of  all  access  applications  and 
decisions  relating  to  such  applications,  including  the 
permits  issued;

(f)  in the case of access to human genetic resource, its use 
is  not  for  the  purposes  contrary  to  ethical  values  or  the 
public  interest;

(k)  the use of the biological resource is not for the development 
of  biological  or  chemical  weapons,  or  for  military  or 
terrorist  purposes;

(f)  in the case of access to human genetic resource, its use 
is  not  for  the  purposes  contrary  to  ethical  values  or  the 
public  interest;

(k)  the use of the biological resource is not for the development 
of  biological  or  chemical  weapons,  or  for  military  or 
terrorist  purposes;

(a)  the  description  of  the  biological  resource  or  traditional 
knowledge  associated  with  the  biological  resource, 
including  available  unique  identifiers;

(a)  inspecting any biological resource, conveyance, machinery, 
contrivance, equipment, book, record, document or other 
article  as  he  considers  necessary;

(a)  to require the production of records, accounts and documents 
and  to  inspect,  examine  and  copy  any  of  the  records, 
accounts  and  documents;

(c)  to provide for special procedures for a specified biological 
resource or a specified collection of biological resource 
to  advance  conservation  of  biodiversity;

(e)  to prescribe the manner for access to a biological resource 
and  traditional  knowledge  associated  with  a  biological 
resource  by  an  authorized  intermediary;

(a)  do  not  intend  to  use  the  biological  resource  or  traditional  knowledge 
associated  with  the  biological  resource,  to  which  the  proposed  action 
relates,  for  commercial  or  potential  commercial  purposes;

(b)  undertake  to  give  a  written  report  on  the  results  of  any  research  on 
a  biological  resource  or  traditional  knowledge  associated  with  the 
biological  resource  to  the  Competent  Authority;
